## Introduction

Enterprise Active Directory environments have spent two decades accumulating hardening guidance, mature detection tooling, and well-understood attack patterns. Red teamers have a deep playbook for on-premises AD: Kerberoasting, DCSync, Pass-the-Hash, Golden Ticket, RBCD abuse. Defenders have Sysmon, EDR, and a rich body of threat intelligence to counter them.

Entra ID (formerly Azure Active Directory) changed the equation. As organizations adopted Microsoft 365, Azure workloads, and hybrid identity models, they created a new bridge between their on-premises Active Directory forests and Microsoft's identity cloud. This bridge — implemented through Azure AD Connect (now Entra Connect), Seamless SSO, Pass-Through Authentication, and device registration — introduced a family of lateral movement primitives that are less well understood, frequently misconfigured, and in many cases bypass controls that defenders spent years building in the on-premises world.

This post documents original research into the pathways by which an attacker with a foothold in an on-premises Active Directory environment can pivot to Entra ID, establish persistent cloud access, and operate in Microsoft 365 and Azure with credentials that are distinct from — and harder to revoke than — the on-premises credentials that were compromised.

We will cover the identity architecture that enables these attacks, deep-dive into the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) mechanism that underpins device-bound SSO, and walk through every major technique in the current red team playbook for hybrid AD-to-cloud lateral movement — including Pass-the-PRT, WANBAN, Office process memory token extraction, browser token theft, Entra Connect database abuse, Seamless SSO silver ticket attacks, and Golden SAML.

